<metadata> <idinfo> <citation> <citeinfo> <origin>King County</origin> <pubdate>20061002</pubdate> <title>WRIA boundaries derived from terrain data - King County only</title> <edition>One</edition> <geoform Sync="TRUE">vector digital data</geoform> <pubinfo> <pubplace>King County, WA</pubplace> <publish>King County</publish> </pubinfo> <othercit>None</othercit> <onlink Sync="TRUE">\\gisimage\images\FTPData\DataStage\topo_wria_kc\topo_wria_kc</onlink></citeinfo> </citation> <descript> <abstract>DRNBASIN is replaced with a higher detail TOPO_CATCHMENT. The difference between the two is DRNBASIN was digitized from existing paper maps based on USGS quad maps in the early 1990s. While the TOPO_CATCHMENT was produced using Arc/Info GRID Watershed commands on 6 foot cell GRIDS built from LIDAR ascii ground model data. Topo_Catchment is higher in accuracy then DRNBASIN</abstract> <purpose>To replace existing King County Watershed layer DRNBASIN with higher accuracy watersheds based on Lidar. Watersheds delineate areas that water collect and flow out to another waterbody, i.e. a Basin, River, Lake or Sound</purpose> <supplinf>Topo_Catchment is the master layer and is dissolved to produce Topo_Basin, Topo_Watershed, and Topo_WRIA by attributes.</supplinf> </descript> <timeperd> <timeinfo> <rngdates> <begdate>20050601</begdate> <enddate>20061004</enddate> </rngdates> </timeinfo> <current>publication date</current> </timeperd> <status> <progress>Complete</progress> <update>As needed</update> </status> <spdom> <bounding> <westbc Sync="TRUE">-122.542057</westbc> <eastbc Sync="TRUE">-121.063186</eastbc> <northbc Sync="TRUE">47.788384</northbc> <southbc Sync="TRUE">47.073373</southbc> </bounding> </spdom> <keywords> <theme> <themekt>Not applicable</themekt> <themekey>hydro</themekey> <themekey>hydrology</themekey> <themekey>none</themekey> </theme> <place> <placekt>Not applicable</placekt> <placekey>King County, WA</placekey> <placekey>Pacific NW</placekey> <placekey>Washington state</placekey> </place> </keywords> <accconst>None</accconst> <useconst>King County data are made available with the understanding that they shall be used exclusively by the obtainer or his/her authorized agents. Some catchments outside of King County have no ID value. Not all Basins have Sub-Basins.</logic> <complete>Topo_Catchment replaces DRNBASIN completely. The area that was updated is King County's Lidar extent. This includes all of King County and Basins in Snohomish that are part of the Lake Washington - Cedar Watershed.</complete> <lineage> <procstep> <procdesc> For each HYDROBASIN or TOPO_BASIN, a project area is built in Arc/Info 9.1 using the AML build_dem.aml. This AML builds a 2000 foot buffered Digital Elevation Model, Accumulation, and Slope grids for the basin area using the Bare Earth or Digital Ground Model Lidar grids. Clip existing WTRCRS per DRNBASIN's attribute BASIN_NAME or HYDROBASIN area. Import WTRCRS to a personal geodatabase. For WTRCRS, add field attributes DEPTH (Short, 4) for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses, RATE (Short, 4) for geometry accuracy rating, and NOTES (Text, 254) for additional information for each line. Create polygon Shapefiles "DEMFIX" and point "PRPT" for each basin. Add field attribute DEPTH (Short, 4) to shapefile "DEMFIX" for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses. Add attribute "CATCHMENT" (Text, 40) to "PRPT" for joining to existing DRNBASIN Polygon Attribute Table </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Create Arcmap project per basin and add basin data. Correct WTRCRS geometry using KC and USGS 2002 orthophotos, Lidar products elevation, slope, hillshade, and contours for referance in Arcmap. Place shapefile PRPT Pour Points per existing DRNBASIN catchments. Calc catchment ID to PRPT attribute "CATCHMENT". Add "DEMFIX" polygons as needed to facilitated water flow over obstacles i.e. roads crossing streams and calculate a depth. Export geodatabase WTRCRS to shapefile WTRCRS After the basin WTRCRS is corrected and Pour Points added for each catchment, the AML mk_ws.aml (Make Watershed) is used to produce the catchments for each basin. The mk_ws.aml converts shapefiles WTRCRS, DEMFIX, and PRPT to coverages. The lines of WTRCRS and polygons of DEMFIX are converted to grids. The grids "burn" or subtract cell values for a stream course into the DEM using the DEPTH value to facilitate the correct flow path though the DEM. Fills the DEM for sinkholes, Finds Flow Direction of the DEM, and the Flow Accumulation of cells. The cells with greater than 40,000 cells flowing into them are extracted to grid STRM40KG, then converted to coverage STRM40KG. PRPT coverage is converted to grid, then snaped using Grid command snappour to the STRM40KG grid. The Grid command WATERSHED deliniates the catchement watershed boundaries to grid WSG (Watershed Grid). Grid WSG is converted to coverage WS (Watershed). In ArcEdit, the existing label points in WS are replaced with the PRPT point labels that have the catchment attribute. The WS is polygon rebuilt, then blank attribute polygons are deleted, and duplicate catchments are dissolved by the same catchment ID. The WS coverage is converted to the shapefile: WSC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">08260000</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> All King County WSC shapefile basins are fitted together using ArcGIS ArcToolBox command Integrate at 15 feet tolerance. Basins are merged together using the ArcToolBox Merge command into a GeoDataBase called DRNBASIN_NEW. Topology is created using "No Gaps" and "No Overlaps" rules. All topology errors are fixed in DRNBASIN_NEW. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> A copy of bigwater is edited to delete the rivers. An existing old copy of DRNBASIN was updated with the modified bigwater layer using the command UPDATE. The updated DRNBASIN is cleaned up to eliminate slivers between bigwater and dnrbasin. The conflated DRNBASIN to Bigwater is UPDATED with DRNBASIN_NEW, dissolved using the attribute catchment to produce the new drnbasin TOPO_CATCHMENT.
TOPO_CATCHMENT is cleaned of slivers, then the 3 child products (Basin, Watershed, and WRIA) are dissolved from topo_catchment. All four levels of topo_catchment are clipped with the King County boundary to produce TOPO_CATCHMENT_KC, TOPO_BASIN_KC, TOPO_WATERSHED_KC, and TOPO_WRIA_KC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Quality control was done by comparing the original DRNBASIN catchments IDs to the new Topo_Catchment catchment IDs. Any missing catchments were added by using the command UPDATE and then MERGING of the sliver polygons generated from the UPDATE around the polygon. Multi part polygons caused by the original MERGING and UPDATE corrections were EXPLODED then MERGED using DRNBASIN as a guide. </procdesc> <srcused Sync="TRUE">J:\basin\topo_catchment.xml</srcused> <procdate>20061017</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">07275200</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Split Upper White River basin into 4 basins: Lower White 100304, Greenwater 10036, Westfork 100305, Upper White stays 100303. Spit Skykomish basin into 6 basins: North Fork 70110, South Fork 70111, Beckler 70113, Miller 70112, Foss 70114, Tye 70115. Corrected Thorton & North Fork Tolt basin boundaries. </procdesc> <procdate>1-16-2008</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc Sync="TRUE">Dataset copied.</procdesc> <time Because it's parcel based, lines will not always align with the ortho photos. A feature in ST_ADDRESS should exist if there is a property with a valid address. A property such as an apartment or condo complex may have many streets within the property but only one street will be shown in ST_ADDRESS, containing the site address. Use TRANS_NETWORK when the lines should more closely match the ortho photos.</abstract><purpose>To provide an addressable address layer. A shapefile is created which contains all new type 1 arcs that have been added to the cadastal base - Boundary - since the last quarterly update. Type 1 arcs are street centerlines. These new centerlines are copied and pasted into the st_address layer and their attributes calculated. Some streets are added that are not centerlines. These streets are found by a review of pin_address - a parcel layer with the house addresses attached - and st_address. If a parcel, or group of parcels, has a house address that doesn't correspond to any street around it, then it is determined that a street is missing. An arc is then added from Boundary into st_address and the attributes calculated. Ortho photos are used to determine which arc should be used to represent the street so that it is positionally accurate.</procdesc><procdate>Unknown</procdate><proccont><cntinfo><cntperp><cntper>Toni Carpenter</cntper><cntorg>King County GIS Center - Client Services</cntorg></cntperp><cntpos>GIS Analyst</cntpos><cntaddr><addrtype>mailing and physical address</addrtype><address>201 S Jackson ST, Suite 700</address><city>Seattle</city><state>WA</state><postal>98104</postal><country>USA</country></cntaddr><cntvoice>206-263-4502</cntvoice><cntemail>toni.carpenter@kingcounty.gov</cntemail></cntinfo></proccont></procstep><procstep><procdesc>Deleted Forest Service Roads from the feature class because they are non addressable. STYLE="text-align:Left;"><DIV><DIV><P><SPAN>KC streets derived from the cadastral database where lines represent the mid-point of the parcel right-of-way. Because it's parcel based, lines will not always align with the ortho photos. A feature in ST_ADDRESS should exist if there is a property with a valid address. A property such as an apartment or condo complex may have many streets within the property but only one street will be shown in ST_ADDRESS, containing the site address. Use TRANS_NETWORK when the lines should more closely match the ortho photos.</SPAN></P></DIV></DIV></DIV></idAbs><idPurp>To provide an addressable address layer. These plats make up Boundary - the cadastral base layer. The zipcode attribute comes from the KC GIS Center zipcode layer. Address ranges come from the pin_address dataset that is derived from Assessor data. The KC_FCC attributes are used to break out the streets into different types: Primary, Major, Connector, Freeway and Local. Street names are sometimes compared to the Exicse Tax Affidavits report.</measDesc></report><report type="DQAbsExtPosAcc" dimension="horizontal"><measDesc>This data set is conflated to the King County Cadastral Base.</measDesc></report><dataLineage><prcStep xmlns=""><stepDesc>St_Address is updated quarterly. A shapefile is created which contains all new type 1 arcs that have been added to the cadastal base - Boundary - since the last quarterly update. Type 1 arcs are street centerlines. These new centerlines are copied and pasted into the st_address layer and their attributes calculated. Some streets are added that are not centerlines. These streets are found by a review of pin_address - a parcel layer with the house addresses attached - and st_address. If a parcel, or group of parcels, has a house address that doesn't correspond to any street around it, then it is determined that a street is missing. An arc is then added from Boundary into st_address and the attributes calculated. Ortho photos are used to determine which arc should be used to represent the street so that it is positionally accurate.</stepDesc><stepDateTm date="unknown">2012-06-20T00:00:00</stepDateTm><stepProc xmlns=""><rpIndName>Toni Carpenter</rpIndName><rpOrgName>King County GIS Center - Client Services</rpOrgName><rpPosName>GIS Analyst</rpPosName><rpCntInfo><cntPhone><voiceNum>206-263-4502</voiceNum></cntPhone><cntAddress addressType="both"><delPoint>201 S Jackson ST, Suite 700</delPoint><city>Seattle</city><adminArea>WA</adminArea><postCode>98104</postCode><country>US</country><eMailAdd>toni.carpenter@kingcounty.gov</eMailAdd></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><role><RoleCd value="009"/></role></stepProc></prcStep><prcStep xmlns=""><stepDesc>Deleted Forest Service Roads from the feature class because they are non addressable. WRIAs were formalized under WAC 173-500-040 and authorized under the Water Resources Act of 1971, RCW 90.54. Ecology was given the responsibility for the development and management of these administrative and planning boundaries. These boundaries represent the administrative under pinning of this agency's business activities. The original WRIA boundary agreements and judgments were reached jointly by Washington's natural resource agencies (Ecology, Natural Resources, Fish and Wildlife) in 1970.</abstract> <purpose>To create a WRIA coverage at a scale of 1:24,000 through the updating of two "like" data sets from different sources. Additionally, to address discrepancies found between the two coverages and determine a "best fit" line through several stages of visual analysis. The development process identified several major objectives as reasoning to update the digital data coverage: To improve the spatial resolution of the data set, To align the WRIA boundaries with 1:24,000 scale hydrology and topography data, To insure of the alignment of the WRIA boundaries to existing county and state boundaries where appropriate, and To have one reconciled set of administrative watershed boundaries (i.e. WADNR's boundaries to nest within the WRIA boundaries)</purpose> <supplinf>Developed with funding from the Department of Ecology's Information Integration Project (IIP). The WRIA data set was derived from a base layer of WAU units courtesy of DNR. The WAU boundaries were input at a scale of 1:24,000 and represent accuracy standards for that scale. Additionally WRIA boundaries were evaluated in areas of discrepancy. In these identified areas, topographical, hydrological, and administrative boundary information was utilized to make an informed decision about the correct position of the boundary. Copied WAU coverage to project directory and dissolved out WRIA polygons by WRIA_NR. 2. Overlaid WRIA100K and dissolved WAU coverage to create discrepancy polygons. 3. Created point discrepancy coverage. 4. Applied selection criteria (polys > 35 acres, points > 750 feet) to discrepancy coverages. 5. Intersected 24K quadrangle and section-township-range coverage with polygon and point discrepancy coverages. 6. Attached attributes of intersected coverages and performed ranking procedure to prioritize the results. 7. Mapped each polygon discrepancy by quadrangle and grouped each map by its associated WRIA basin. 8. All WRIA maps were assembled into books representing each WRIA and its discrepancies. 9. Microsoft Access database developed to help manage and report project data (editing, analysis decisions, comments). 10. Visual analysis of each discrepancy performed using the map books (stage 1). 11. Additional analysis performed using USGS DRGs at 1:24,000 scale as well as, in house hydrology and administrative boundary data sets (stage 2). 12. Project edits carried out based on the two stages of analysis.
The project was revisited in March of 2000 using two additional methods of analysis. First, the WRIA24K boundaries were overlaid with statewide 24K scale hydrology coverage to check for stream crossings. A 10 foot buffer was used on either side of the WRIA boundary to limit the size of the output data set. Stream crossings were then evaluated for relevance. Additionally, a general overview of the WRIA boundaries as done by examining each WRIA again the 24K scale USGS DRGs. This was done as an additional check for unnecessary stream crossings and drainage errors.</procdesc> <procdate>20000403</procdate> <proccont> <cntinfo> <cntorgp> <cntorg>Washington State Department of Ecology</cntorg> <cntper>Mike Woodall</cntper> </cntorgp> <cntpos>GIS Analyst/Cartographer</cntpos> <cntaddr> <addrtype>mailing address</addrtype> <address>PO Box 47600</address> <city>Olympia</city> <state>Washington</state> <postal>98504-7600</postal> <country>United States of America</country> </cntaddr> <cntvoice>(360) 407-6088</cntvoice> <cntemail>miwo461@ecy.wa.gov</cntemail> <hours>6am-3pm, M-F</hours> </cntinfo> </proccont> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc>Boundary update area, WRIA's 8-9 at Rock Creek. ESRI ArcCatalog 9.3.1.3000</native><descript><langdata Sync="TRUE">en</langdata><abstract>This Parcel layer utilizes the geometry and schema changes in the new cadastral geodatabase model. This includes stacked polygon geometry for undivided interest and vertical parcels and new coded value domain for item MINOR, described below.</abstract><purpose>The new parcel_area Feature Class, derived from the new Cadastral Geodatabase (KCAM), replaces the countywide parcel coverage and shapefile previously derived from Recdnet data.</purpose><supplinf>Items PIN, MAJOR, MINOR, will still be present in both SDE feature class and shapefile, however coded value changes for item MINOR are as follows:
5555 will now be coded as 'ROAD' 5999 will now be coded as 'RDNA' (Road No Access) 6666 (type 5 water) will now be coded as 'HYDR' 6666 (type 1 property) will now be coded as 'UNKN' (Unknown) 7777 will now be coded as 'TRCT' (Tract with undivided interest) 8888 will now be coded as '0000' (4-zeros) 9999 will now be coded 'PUBL'
The other significant change is that now Undivided Interest and Vertical parcels are represented by stacked polygon geometry. One example of stacked polygon geometry for an Undivided Interest can be found in PIN = 4088801605.</supplinf></descript><citation><citeinfo><origin>King County</origin><pubdate>20061101</pubdate><title>King County Parcels</title><ftname Sync="TRUE">KCAM.CADMIN.Parcel</ftname><geoform Sync="TRUE">vector digital data</geoform><onlink>none</onlink><edition>1.0</edition></citeinfo></citation><timeperd><current>publication date</current><timeinfo><sngdate><caldate>2006 and Ongoing</caldate></sngdate></timeinfo></timeperd><status><progress>Complete</progress><update>Weekly</update></status><spdom><bounding><westbc Sync="TRUE">-122.550394</westbc><eastbc Sync="TRUE">-121.084384</eastbc><northbc Sync="TRUE">47.788447</northbc><southbc Sync="TRUE">47.072060</southbc></bounding><lboundng><leftbc Sync="TRUE">1218256.910000</leftbc><rightbc Sync="TRUE">1577865.300000</rightbc><bottombc Sync="TRUE">30932.680000</bottombc><topbc Sync="TRUE">287704.244000</topbc></lboundng></spdom><keywords><theme><themekt>none</themekt><themekey>Parcel</themekey><themekey>Tax Parcel</themekey><themekey>Property</themekey></theme><place><placekt>none</placekt><placekey>King County</placekey></place></keywords><accconst>For internal use only. <metadata> <idinfo> <citation> <citeinfo> <origin>King County</origin> <pubdate>20061002</pubdate> <title>Watershed boundaries derived from terrain data - King County only</title> <edition>One</edition> <geoform Sync="TRUE">vector digital data</geoform> <pubinfo> <pubplace>King County, WA</pubplace> <publish>King County</publish> </pubinfo> <othercit>None</othercit> <onlink Sync="TRUE">\\gisimage\images\FTPData\DataStage\topo_watershed_kc\topo_watershed_kc</onlink></citeinfo> </citation> <descript> <abstract>DRNBASIN is replaced with a higher detail TOPO_CATCHMENT. The difference between the two is DRNBASIN was digitized from existing paper maps based on USGS quad maps in the early 1990s. While the TOPO_CATCHMENT was produced using Arc/Info GRID Watershed commands on 6 foot cell GRIDS built from LIDAR ascii ground model data. Topo_Catchment is higher in accuracy then DRNBASIN</abstract> <purpose>To replace existing King County Watershed layer DRNBASIN with higher accuracy watersheds based on Lidar. Watersheds delineate areas that water collect and flow out to another waterbody, i.e. a Basin, River, Lake or Sound</purpose> <supplinf>Topo_Catchment is the master layer and is dissolved to produce Topo_Basin, Topo_Watershed, and Topo_WRIA by attributes.</supplinf> </descript> <timeperd> <timeinfo> <rngdates> <begdate>20050601</begdate> <enddate>20061004</enddate> </rngdates> </timeinfo> <current>publication date</current> </timeperd> <status> <progress>Complete</progress> <update>As needed</update> </status> <spdom> <bounding> <westbc Sync="TRUE">-122.542057</westbc> <eastbc Sync="TRUE">-121.063186</eastbc> <northbc Sync="TRUE">47.788384</northbc> <southbc Sync="TRUE">47.073373</southbc> </bounding> </spdom> <keywords> <theme> <themekt>Not applicable</themekt> <themekey>hydro</themekey> <themekey>hydrology</themekey> <themekey>none</themekey> </theme> <place> <placekt>Not applicable</placekt> <placekey>King County, WA</placekey> <placekey>Pacific NW</placekey> <placekey>Washington state</placekey> </place> </keywords> <accconst>None</accconst> <useconst>King County data are made available with the understanding that they shall be used exclusively by the obtainer or his/her authorized agents. Some catchments outside of King County have no ID value. Not all Basins have Sub-Basins.</logic> <complete>Topo_Catchment replaces DRNBASIN completely. The area that was updated is King County's Lidar extent. This includes all of King County and Basins in Snohomish that are part of the Lake Washington - Cedar Watershed.</complete> <lineage> <procstep> <procdesc> For each HYDROBASIN or TOPO_BASIN, a project area is built in Arc/Info 9.1 using the AML build_dem.aml. This AML builds a 2000 foot buffered Digital Elevation Model, Accumulation, and Slope grids for the basin area using the Bare Earth or Digital Ground Model Lidar grids. Clip existing WTRCRS per DRNBASIN's attribute BASIN_NAME or HYDROBASIN area. Import WTRCRS to a personal geodatabase. For WTRCRS, add field attributes DEPTH (Short, 4) for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses, RATE (Short, 4) for geometry accuracy rating, and NOTES (Text, 254) for additional information for each line. Create polygon Shapefiles "DEMFIX" and point "PRPT" for each basin. Add field attribute DEPTH (Short, 4) to shapefile "DEMFIX" for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses. Add attribute "CATCHMENT" (Text, 40) to "PRPT" for joining to existing DRNBASIN Polygon Attribute Table </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Create Arcmap project per basin and add basin data. Correct WTRCRS geometry using KC and USGS 2002 orthophotos, Lidar products elevation, slope, hillshade, and contours for referance in Arcmap. Place shapefile PRPT Pour Points per existing DRNBASIN catchments. Calc catchment ID to PRPT attribute "CATCHMENT". Add "DEMFIX" polygons as needed to facilitated water flow over obstacles i.e. roads crossing streams and calculate a depth. Export geodatabase WTRCRS to shapefile WTRCRS After the basin WTRCRS is corrected and Pour Points added for each catchment, the AML mk_ws.aml (Make Watershed) is used to produce the catchments for each basin. The mk_ws.aml converts shapefiles WTRCRS, DEMFIX, and PRPT to coverages. The lines of WTRCRS and polygons of DEMFIX are converted to grids. The grids "burn" or subtract cell values for a stream course into the DEM using the DEPTH value to facilitate the correct flow path though the DEM. Fills the DEM for sinkholes, Finds Flow Direction of the DEM, and the Flow Accumulation of cells. The cells with greater than 40,000 cells flowing into them are extracted to grid STRM40KG, then converted to coverage STRM40KG. PRPT coverage is converted to grid, then snaped using Grid command snappour to the STRM40KG grid. The Grid command WATERSHED deliniates the catchement watershed boundaries to grid WSG (Watershed Grid). Grid WSG is converted to coverage WS (Watershed). In ArcEdit, the existing label points in WS are replaced with the PRPT point labels that have the catchment attribute. The WS is polygon rebuilt, then blank attribute polygons are deleted, and duplicate catchments are dissolved by the same catchment ID. The WS coverage is converted to the shapefile: WSC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">08260000</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> All King County WSC shapefile basins are fitted together using ArcGIS ArcToolBox command Integrate at 15 feet tolerance. Basins are merged together using the ArcToolBox Merge command into a GeoDataBase called DRNBASIN_NEW. Topology is created using "No Gaps" and "No Overlaps" rules. All topology errors are fixed in DRNBASIN_NEW. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> A copy of bigwater is edited to delete the rivers. An existing old copy of DRNBASIN was updated with the modified bigwater layer using the command UPDATE. The updated DRNBASIN is cleaned up to eliminate slivers between bigwater and dnrbasin. The conflated DRNBASIN to Bigwater is UPDATED with DRNBASIN_NEW, dissolved using the attribute catchment to produce the new drnbasin TOPO_CATCHMENT.
TOPO_CATCHMENT is cleaned of slivers, then the 3 child products (Basin, Watershed, and WRIA) are dissolved from topo_catchment. All four levels of topo_catchment are clipped with the King County boundary to produce TOPO_CATCHMENT_KC, TOPO_BASIN_KC, TOPO_WATERSHED_KC, and TOPO_WRIA_KC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Quality control was done by comparing the original DRNBASIN catchments IDs to the new Topo_Catchment catchment IDs. Any missing catchments were added by using the command UPDATE and then MERGING of the sliver polygons generated from the UPDATE around the polygon. Multi part polygons caused by the original MERGING and UPDATE corrections were EXPLODED then MERGED using DRNBASIN as a guide. </procdesc> <srcused Sync="TRUE">J:\basin\topo_catchment.xml</srcused> <procdate>20061017</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">07275200</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Split Upper White River basin into 4 basins: Lower White 100304, Greenwater 10036, Westfork 100305, Upper White stays 100303. Spit Skykomish basin into 6 basins: North Fork 70110, South Fork 70111, Beckler 70113, Miller 70112, Foss 70114, Tye 70115. Corrected Thorton & North Fork Tolt basin boundaries. </procdesc> <procdate>1-16-2008</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc Sync="TRUE">Dataset copied.</procdesc> <time Sync="TRUE">08203900</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc>Each time TOPO_CATCHMENT is updated this feature class is updated by a dissolve and then clipped to the King County boundary.</procdesc> <metadata> <idinfo> <citation> <citeinfo> <origin>King County</origin> <pubdate>20061002</pubdate> <title>Basin boundaries derived from terrain data - King County only</title> <edition>One</edition> <geoform Sync="TRUE">vector digital data</geoform> <pubinfo> <pubplace>King County, WA</pubplace> <publish>King County</publish> </pubinfo> <othercit>None</othercit> <onlink Sync="TRUE">\\gisimage\images\FTPData\DataStage\topo_basin_kc\topo_basin_kc</onlink></citeinfo> </citation> <descript> <abstract>DRNBASIN is replaced with a higher detail TOPO_CATCHMENT. The difference between the two is DRNBASIN was digitized from existing paper maps based on USGS quad maps in the early 1990s. While the TOPO_CATCHMENT was produced using Arc/Info GRID Watershed commands on 6 foot cell GRIDS built from LIDAR ascii ground model data. Topo_Catchment is higher in accuracy then DRNBASIN</abstract> <purpose>To replace existing King County Watershed layer DRNBASIN with higher accuracy watersheds based on Lidar. Watersheds delineate areas that water collect and flow out to another waterbody, i.e. a Basin, River, Lake or Sound</purpose> <supplinf>Topo_Catchment is the master layer and is dissolved to produce Topo_Basin, Topo_Watershed, and Topo_WRIA by attributes.</supplinf> </descript> <timeperd> <timeinfo> <rngdates> <begdate>20050601</begdate> <enddate>20061004</enddate> </rngdates> </timeinfo> <current>publication date</current> </timeperd> <status> <progress>Complete</progress> <update>As needed</update> </status> <spdom> <bounding> <westbc Sync="TRUE">-122.542057</westbc> <eastbc Sync="TRUE">-121.063186</eastbc> <northbc Sync="TRUE">47.788384</northbc> <southbc Sync="TRUE">47.073373</southbc> </bounding> </spdom> <keywords> <theme> <themekt>Not applicable</themekt> <themekey>hydro</themekey> <themekey>hydrology</themekey> <themekey>none</themekey> </theme> <place> <placekt>Not applicable</placekt> <placekey>King County, WA</placekey> <placekey>Pacific NW</placekey> <placekey>Washington state</placekey> </place> </keywords> <accconst>None</accconst> <useconst>King County data are made available with the understanding that they shall be used exclusively by the obtainer or his/her authorized agents. Some catchments outside of King County have no ID value. Not all Basins have Sub-Basins.</logic> <complete>Topo_Catchment replaces DRNBASIN completely. The area that was updated is King County's Lidar extent. This includes all of King County and Basins in Snohomish that are part of the Lake Washington - Cedar Watershed.</complete> <lineage> <procstep> <procdesc> For each HYDROBASIN or TOPO_BASIN, a project area is built in Arc/Info 9.1 using the AML build_dem.aml. This AML builds a 2000 foot buffered Digital Elevation Model, Accumulation, and Slope grids for the basin area using the Bare Earth or Digital Ground Model Lidar grids. Clip existing WTRCRS per DRNBASIN's attribute BASIN_NAME or HYDROBASIN area. Import WTRCRS to a personal geodatabase. For WTRCRS, add field attributes DEPTH (Short, 4) for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses, RATE (Short, 4) for geometry accuracy rating, and NOTES (Text, 254) for additional information for each line. Create polygon Shapefiles "DEMFIX" and point "PRPT" for each basin. Add field attribute DEPTH (Short, 4) to shapefile "DEMFIX" for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses. Add attribute "CATCHMENT" (Text, 40) to "PRPT" for joining to existing DRNBASIN Polygon Attribute Table </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Create Arcmap project per basin and add basin data. Correct WTRCRS geometry using KC and USGS 2002 orthophotos, Lidar products elevation, slope, hillshade, and contours for referance in Arcmap. Place shapefile PRPT Pour Points per existing DRNBASIN catchments. Calc catchment ID to PRPT attribute "CATCHMENT". Add "DEMFIX" polygons as needed to facilitated water flow over obstacles i.e. roads crossing streams and calculate a depth. Export geodatabase WTRCRS to shapefile WTRCRS After the basin WTRCRS is corrected and Pour Points added for each catchment, the AML mk_ws.aml (Make Watershed) is used to produce the catchments for each basin. The mk_ws.aml converts shapefiles WTRCRS, DEMFIX, and PRPT to coverages. The lines of WTRCRS and polygons of DEMFIX are converted to grids. The grids "burn" or subtract cell values for a stream course into the DEM using the DEPTH value to facilitate the correct flow path though the DEM. Fills the DEM for sinkholes, Finds Flow Direction of the DEM, and the Flow Accumulation of cells. The cells with greater than 40,000 cells flowing into them are extracted to grid STRM40KG, then converted to coverage STRM40KG. PRPT coverage is converted to grid, then snaped using Grid command snappour to the STRM40KG grid. The Grid command WATERSHED deliniates the catchement watershed boundaries to grid WSG (Watershed Grid). Grid WSG is converted to coverage WS (Watershed). In ArcEdit, the existing label points in WS are replaced with the PRPT point labels that have the catchment attribute. The WS is polygon rebuilt, then blank attribute polygons are deleted, and duplicate catchments are dissolved by the same catchment ID. The WS coverage is converted to the shapefile: WSC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">08260000</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> All King County WSC shapefile basins are fitted together using ArcGIS ArcToolBox command Integrate at 15 feet tolerance. Basins are merged together using the ArcToolBox Merge command into a GeoDataBase called DRNBASIN_NEW. Topology is created using "No Gaps" and "No Overlaps" rules. All topology errors are fixed in DRNBASIN_NEW. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> A copy of bigwater is edited to delete the rivers. An existing old copy of DRNBASIN was updated with the modified bigwater layer using the command UPDATE. The updated DRNBASIN is cleaned up to eliminate slivers between bigwater and dnrbasin. The conflated DRNBASIN to Bigwater is UPDATED with DRNBASIN_NEW, dissolved using the attribute catchment to produce the new drnbasin TOPO_CATCHMENT.
TOPO_CATCHMENT is cleaned of slivers, then the 3 child products (Basin, Watershed, and WRIA) are dissolved from topo_catchment. All four levels of topo_catchment are clipped with the King County boundary to produce TOPO_CATCHMENT_KC, TOPO_BASIN_KC, TOPO_WATERSHED_KC, and TOPO_WRIA_KC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Quality control was done by comparing the original DRNBASIN catchments IDs to the new Topo_Catchment catchment IDs. Any missing catchments were added by using the command UPDATE and then MERGING of the sliver polygons generated from the UPDATE around the polygon. Multi part polygons caused by the original MERGING and UPDATE corrections were EXPLODED then MERGED using DRNBASIN as a guide. </procdesc> <srcused Sync="TRUE">J:\basin\topo_catchment.xml</srcused> <procdate>20061017</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">07275200</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Split Upper White River basin into 4 basins: Lower White 100304, Greenwater 10036, Westfork 100305, Upper White stays 100303. Spit Skykomish basin into 6 basins: North Fork 70110, South Fork 70111, Beckler 70113, Miller 70112, Foss 70114, Tye 70115. Corrected Thorton & North Fork Tolt basin boundaries. </procdesc> <procdate>1-16-2008</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc Sync="TRUE">Dataset copied.</procdesc> <time Sync="TRUE">08203900</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc>Each time TOPO_CATCHMENT is updated this feature class is updated by a dissolve and then clipped to the King County boundary.</procdesc> These plats make up Boundary - the cadastral base layer. The zipcode attribute comes from the KC GIS Center zipcode layer. Address ranges come from the pin_address dataset that is derived from Assessor data. The KC_FCC attributes are used to break out the streets into different types: Primary, Major, Connector, Freeway and Local. A shapefile is created which contains all new type 1 arcs that have been added to the cadastal base - Boundary - since the last quarterly update. Type 1 arcs are street centerlines. These new centerlines are copied and pasted into the st_address layer and their attributes calculated. Some streets are added that are not centerlines. These streets are found by a review of pin_address - a parcel layer with the house addresses attached - and st_address. If a parcel, or group of parcels, has a house address that doesn't correspond to any street around it, then it is determined that a street is missing. An arc is then added from Boundary into st_address and the attributes calculated. Ortho photos are used to determine which arc should be used to represent the street so that it is positionally accurate.</procdesc><procdate>Unknown</procdate><proccont><cntinfo><cntperp><cntper>Toni Carpenter</cntper><cntorg>King County GIS Center - Client Services</cntorg></cntperp><cntpos>GIS Analyst</cntpos><cntaddr><addrtype>mailing and physical address</addrtype><address>201 S Jackson ST, Suite 700</address><city>Seattle</city><state>WA</state><postal>98104</postal><country>USA</country></cntaddr><cntvoice>206-263-4502</cntvoice><cntemail>toni.carpenter@kingcounty.gov</cntemail></cntinfo></proccont></procstep><procstep><procdesc>Deleted Forest Service Roads from the feature class because they are non addressable. STYLE="text-align:Left;"><DIV><DIV><P><SPAN>KC streets derived from the cadastral database where lines represent the mid-point of the parcel right-of-way. Because it's parcel based, lines will not always align with the ortho photos. A feature in ST_ADDRESS should exist if there is a property with a valid address. A property such as an apartment or condo complex may have many streets within the property but only one street will be shown in ST_ADDRESS, containing the site address. Use TRANS_NETWORK when the lines should more closely match the ortho photos.</SPAN></P></DIV></DIV></DIV></idAbs><idPurp>To provide an addressable address layer. These plats make up Boundary - the cadastral base layer. The zipcode attribute comes from the KC GIS Center zipcode layer. Address ranges come from the pin_address dataset that is derived from Assessor data. The KC_FCC attributes are used to break out the streets into different types: Primary, Major, Connector, Freeway and Local. Street names are sometimes compared to the Exicse Tax Affidavits report.</measDesc></report><report type="DQAbsExtPosAcc" dimension="horizontal"><measDesc>This data set is conflated to the King County Cadastral Base.</measDesc></report><dataLineage><prcStep xmlns=""><stepDesc>St_Address is updated quarterly. A shapefile is created which contains all new type 1 arcs that have been added to the cadastal base - Boundary - since the last quarterly update. Type 1 arcs are street centerlines. These new centerlines are copied and pasted into the st_address layer and their attributes calculated. Some streets are added that are not centerlines. These streets are found by a review of pin_address - a parcel layer with the house addresses attached - and st_address. If a parcel, or group of parcels, has a house address that doesn't correspond to any street around it, then it is determined that a street is missing. An arc is then added from Boundary into st_address and the attributes calculated. Ortho photos are used to determine which arc should be used to represent the street so that it is positionally accurate.</stepDesc><stepDateTm date="unknown">2012-06-20T00:00:00</stepDateTm><stepProc xmlns=""><rpIndName>Toni Carpenter</rpIndName><rpOrgName>King County GIS Center - Client Services</rpOrgName><rpPosName>GIS Analyst</rpPosName><rpCntInfo><cntPhone><voiceNum>206-263-4502</voiceNum></cntPhone><cntAddress addressType="both"><delPoint>201 S Jackson ST, Suite 700</delPoint><city>Seattle</city><adminArea>WA</adminArea><postCode>98104</postCode><country>US</country><eMailAdd>toni.carpenter@kingcounty.gov</eMailAdd></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><role><RoleCd value="009"/></role></stepProc></prcStep><prcStep xmlns=""><stepDesc>Deleted Forest Service Roads from the feature class because they are non addressable. geodatabase model. This includes stacked polygon geometry for undivided interest and vertical parcels and new coded value domain for item MINOR, described below.</abstract><purpose>The new parcel_area Feature Class, derived from the new Cadastral Geodatabase (KCAM), replaces the countywide parcel coverage and shapefile previously derived from Recdnet data.</purpose><supplinf>Items PIN, MAJOR, MINOR, will still be present in both SDE feature class and shapefile, however coded value changes for item MINOR are as follows:
5555 will now be coded as 'ROAD' 5999 will now be coded as 'RDNA' (Road No Access) 6666 (type 5 water) will now be coded as 'HYDR' 6666 (type 1 property) will now be coded as 'UNKN' (Unknown) 7777 will now be coded as 'TRCT' (Tract with undivided interest) 8888 will now be coded as '0000' (4-zeros) 9999 will now be coded 'PUBL'
The other significant change is that now Undivided Interest and Vertical parcels are represented by stacked polygon geometry. One example of stacked polygon geometry for an Undivided Interest can be found in PIN = 4088801605.</supplinf></descript><citation><citeinfo><origin>King County</origin><pubdate>20061101</pubdate><title>King County Parcels</title><ftname Sync="TRUE">KCAM.CADMIN.Parcel</ftname><geoform Sync="TRUE">vector digital data</geoform><onlink>none</onlink><edition>1.0</edition></citeinfo></citation><timeperd><current>publication date</current><timeinfo><sngdate><caldate>2006 and Ongoing</caldate></sngdate></timeinfo></timeperd><status><progress>Complete</progress><update>Weekly</update></status><spdom><bounding><westbc Sync="TRUE">-122.550394</westbc><eastbc Sync="TRUE">-121.084384</eastbc><northbc Sync="TRUE">47.788447</northbc><southbc Sync="TRUE">47.072060</southbc></bounding><lboundng><leftbc Sync="TRUE">1218256.910000</leftbc><rightbc Sync="TRUE">1577865.300000</rightbc><bottombc Sync="TRUE">30932.680000</bottombc><topbc Sync="TRUE">287704.244000</topbc></lboundng></spdom><keywords><theme><themekt>none</themekt><themekey>Parcel</themekey><themekey>Tax Parcel</themekey><themekey>Property</themekey></theme><place><placekt>none</placekt><placekey>King County</placekey></place></keywords><accconst>For internal use only. <metadata><idinfo><citation><citeinfo><origin>King County</origin><pubdate>20050725</pubdate><title>Street Address</title><edition>One</edition><geoform Sync="TRUE">vector digital data</geoform><pubinfo><pubplace>King County, WA</pubplace><publish>King County</publish></pubinfo><othercit>None</othercit><onlink Sync="TRUE">Service=sde:sqlserver:gisprod; Database=maint; Version=sde.DEFAULT</onlink></citeinfo></citation><descript><abstract>KC streets derived from the cadastral database where lines represent the mid-point of the parcel right-of-way. Because it's parcel based, lines will not always align with the ortho photos. A feature in ST_ADDRESS should exist if there is a property with a valid address. A property such as an apartment or condo complex may have many streets within the property but only one street will be shown in ST_ADDRESS, containing the site address. Use TRANS_NETWORK when the lines should more closely match the ortho photos.</abstract><purpose>To provide an addressable address layer. Best for symbolizing road classes and for cartographic representation.</purpose><supplinf>None</supplinf></descript><timeperd><timeinfo><sngdate><caldate>20110908</caldate></sngdate></timeinfo><current>publication date</current></timeperd><status><progress>In work</progress><update>Quarterly</update></status><spdom><bounding><westbc Sync="TRUE">-122.635648</westbc><eastbc Sync="TRUE">-121.085427</eastbc><northbc Sync="TRUE">47.788335</northbc><southbc Sync="TRUE">47.074699</southbc></bounding></spdom><keywords><place><placekt>Not applicable</placekt><placekey>King County, WA</placekey><placekey>Pacific NW</placekey><placekey>Washington state</placekey></place><theme><themekey>none</themekey><themekey>transportation</themekey></theme></keywords><accconst>None</accconst><useconst>King County data are made available with the understanding that they shall be used exclusively by the obtainer or his/her authorized agents. Digital products may not be reproduced or redistributed in any form or by any means without the express written authorization of King County.</useconst><ptcontac><cntinfo><cntperp><cntper>Toni Carpenter</cntper><cntorg>King County GIS Center</cntorg></cntperp><cntpos>Client Services GIS Analyst</cntpos><cntaddr><addrtype>mailing and physical address</addrtype><address>201 S Jackson St, Suite 700</address><city>Seattle</city><state>WA</state><postal>98104</postal><country>USA</country></cntaddr><cntvoice>206-263-4502</cntvoice><cntemail>toni.carpenter@kingcounty.gov</cntemail></cntinfo></ptcontac><browse><browsen>http://www5.kingcounty.gov/sdc/DataImages/st_address.jpg</browsen><browsed>JPG File of layer overlain on base of WA counties or local cities</browsed><browset>JPG</browset></browse><native Sync="TRUE">Microsoft Windows XP Version 5.1 (Build 2600) Service Pack 3; ESRI ArcCatalog 9.3.1.1850</native></idinfo><dataqual><attracc><attraccr>The street name attributes are taken from plats that the Assessor's office creates. These plats make up Boundary - the cadastral base layer. The zipcode attribute comes from the KC GIS Center zipcode layer. Address ranges come from the pin_address dataset that is derived from Assessor data. The KC_FCC attributes are used to break out the streets into different types: Primary, Major, Connector, Freeway and Local. Street names are sometimes compared to the Exicse Tax Affidavits report.</attraccr></attracc><logic>Each arc contains a name, zipcode, directional address and type (KC_FCC).</logic><complete>Contains all known streets within King County.</complete><posacc><horizpa><horizpar>This data set is conflated to the King County Cadastral Base.</horizpar></horizpa></posacc><lineage><srcinfo><srctime><timeinfo><sngdate><caldate>12/30/2008</caldate></sngdate></timeinfo><srccurr>publication date</srccurr></srctime></srcinfo><procstep><procdesc>St_Address is updated quarterly. A shapefile is created which contains all new type 1 arcs that have been added to the cadastal base - Boundary - since the last quarterly update. Type 1 arcs are street centerlines. These new centerlines are copied and pasted into the st_address layer and their attributes calculated. Some streets are added that are not centerlines. These streets are found by a review of pin_address - a parcel layer with the house addresses attached - and st_address. If a parcel, or group of parcels, has a house address that doesn't correspond to any street around it, then it is determined that a street is missing. An arc is then added from Boundary into st_address and the attributes calculated. Ortho photos are used to determine which arc should be used to represent the street so that it is positionally accurate.</procdesc><procdate>Unknown</procdate><proccont><cntinfo><cntperp><cntper>Toni Carpenter</cntper><cntorg>King County GIS Center - Client Services</cntorg></cntperp><cntpos>GIS Analyst</cntpos><cntaddr><addrtype>mailing and physical address</addrtype><address>201 S Jackson ST, Suite 700</address><city>Seattle</city><state>WA</state><postal>98104</postal><country>USA</country></cntaddr><cntvoice>206-263-4502</cntvoice><cntemail>toni.carpenter@kingcounty.gov</cntemail></cntinfo></proccont></procstep><procstep><procdesc>Deleted Forest Service Roads from the feature class because they are non addressable. STYLE="text-align:Left;"><DIV><DIV><P><SPAN>KC streets derived from the cadastral database where lines represent the mid-point of the parcel right-of-way. Because it's parcel based, lines will not always align with the ortho photos. A feature in ST_ADDRESS should exist if there is a property with a valid address. A property such as an apartment or condo complex may have many streets within the property but only one street will be shown in ST_ADDRESS, containing the site address. Use TRANS_NETWORK when the lines should more closely match the ortho photos.</SPAN></P></DIV></DIV></DIV></idAbs><idPurp>To provide an addressable address layer. These plats make up Boundary - the cadastral base layer. The zipcode attribute comes from the KC GIS Center zipcode layer. Address ranges come from the pin_address dataset that is derived from Assessor data. The KC_FCC attributes are used to break out the streets into different types: Primary, Major, Connector, Freeway and Local. Street names are sometimes compared to the Exicse Tax Affidavits report.</measDesc></report><report type="DQAbsExtPosAcc" dimension="horizontal"><measDesc>This data set is conflated to the King County Cadastral Base.</measDesc></report><dataLineage><prcStep xmlns=""><stepDesc>St_Address is updated quarterly. A shapefile is created which contains all new type 1 arcs that have been added to the cadastal base - Boundary - since the last quarterly update. Type 1 arcs are street centerlines. These new centerlines are copied and pasted into the st_address layer and their attributes calculated. Some streets are added that are not centerlines. These streets are found by a review of pin_address - a parcel layer with the house addresses attached - and st_address. If a parcel, or group of parcels, has a house address that doesn't correspond to any street around it, then it is determined that a street is missing. An arc is then added from Boundary into st_address and the attributes calculated. Ortho photos are used to determine which arc should be used to represent the street so that it is positionally accurate.</stepDesc><stepDateTm date="unknown">2012-06-20T00:00:00</stepDateTm><stepProc xmlns=""><rpIndName>Toni Carpenter</rpIndName><rpOrgName>King County GIS Center - Client Services</rpOrgName><rpPosName>GIS Analyst</rpPosName><rpCntInfo><cntPhone><voiceNum>206-263-4502</voiceNum></cntPhone><cntAddress addressType="both"><delPoint>201 S Jackson ST, Suite 700</delPoint><city>Seattle</city><adminArea>WA</adminArea><postCode>98104</postCode><country>US</country><eMailAdd>toni.carpenter@kingcounty.gov</eMailAdd></cntAddress></rpCntInfo><role><RoleCd value="009"/></role></stepProc></prcStep><prcStep xmlns=""><stepDesc>Deleted Forest Service Roads from the feature class because they are non addressable. The difference between the two is DRNBASIN was digitized from existing paper maps based on USGS quad maps in the early 1990s. While the TOPO_CATCHMENT was produced using Arc/Info GRID Watershed commands on 6 foot cell GRIDS built from LIDAR ascii ground model data. Topo_Catchment is higher in accuracy then DRNBASIN</abstract> <purpose>To replace existing King County Watershed layer DRNBASIN with higher accuracy watersheds based on Lidar. Watersheds delineate areas that water collect and flow out to another waterbody, i.e. a Basin, River, Lake or Sound</purpose> <supplinf>Topo_Catchment is the master layer and is dissolved to produce Topo_Basin, Topo_Watershed, and Topo_WRIA by attributes.</supplinf> </descript> <timeperd> <timeinfo> <rngdates> <begdate>20050601</begdate> <enddate>20061004</enddate> </rngdates> </timeinfo> <current>publication date</current> </timeperd> <status> <progress>Complete</progress> <update>As needed</update> </status> <spdom> <bounding> <westbc Sync="TRUE">-122.542057</westbc> <eastbc Sync="TRUE">-121.063186</eastbc> <northbc Sync="TRUE">47.788384</northbc> <southbc Sync="TRUE">47.073373</southbc> </bounding> </spdom> <keywords> <theme> <themekt>Not applicable</themekt> <themekey>hydro</themekey> <themekey>hydrology</themekey> <themekey>none</themekey> </theme> <place> <placekt>Not applicable</placekt> <placekey>King County, WA</placekey> <placekey>Pacific NW</placekey> <placekey>Washington state</placekey> </place> </keywords> <accconst>None</accconst> <useconst>King County data are made available with the understanding that they shall be used exclusively by the obtainer or his/her authorized agents. Some catchments outside of King County have no ID value. Not all Basins have Sub-Basins.</logic> <complete>Topo_Catchment replaces DRNBASIN completely. The area that was updated is King County's Lidar extent. This includes all of King County and Basins in Snohomish that are part of the Lake Washington - Cedar Watershed.</complete> <lineage> <procstep> <procdesc> For each HYDROBASIN or TOPO_BASIN, a project area is built in Arc/Info 9.1 using the AML build_dem.aml. This AML builds a 2000 foot buffered Digital Elevation Model, Accumulation, and Slope grids for the basin area using the Bare Earth or Digital Ground Model Lidar grids. Clip existing WTRCRS per DRNBASIN's attribute BASIN_NAME or HYDROBASIN area. Import WTRCRS to a personal geodatabase. For WTRCRS, add field attributes DEPTH (Short, 4) for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses, RATE (Short, 4) for geometry accuracy rating, and NOTES (Text, 254) for additional information for each line. Create polygon Shapefiles "DEMFIX" and point "PRPT" for each basin. Add field attribute DEPTH (Short, 4) to shapefile "DEMFIX" for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses. Add attribute "CATCHMENT" (Text, 40) to "PRPT" for joining to existing DRNBASIN Polygon Attribute Table </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Create Arcmap project per basin and add basin data. Correct WTRCRS geometry using KC and USGS 2002 orthophotos, Lidar products elevation, slope, hillshade, and contours for referance in Arcmap. Place shapefile PRPT Pour Points per existing DRNBASIN catchments. Calc catchment ID to PRPT attribute "CATCHMENT". Add "DEMFIX" polygons as needed to facilitated water flow over obstacles i.e. roads crossing streams and calculate a depth. Export geodatabase WTRCRS to shapefile WTRCRS After the basin WTRCRS is corrected and Pour Points added for each catchment, the AML mk_ws.aml (Make Watershed) is used to produce the catchments for each basin. The mk_ws.aml converts shapefiles WTRCRS, DEMFIX, and PRPT to coverages. The lines of WTRCRS and polygons of DEMFIX are converted to grids. The grids "burn" or subtract cell values for a stream course into the DEM using the DEPTH value to facilitate the correct flow path though the DEM. Fills the DEM for sinkholes, Finds Flow Direction of the DEM, and the Flow Accumulation of cells. The cells with greater than 40,000 cells flowing into them are extracted to grid STRM40KG, then converted to coverage STRM40KG. PRPT coverage is converted to grid, then snaped using Grid command snappour to the STRM40KG grid. The Grid command WATERSHED deliniates the catchement watershed boundaries to grid WSG (Watershed Grid). Grid WSG is converted to coverage WS (Watershed). In ArcEdit, the existing label points in WS are replaced with the PRPT point labels that have the catchment attribute. The WS is polygon rebuilt, then blank attribute polygons are deleted, and duplicate catchments are dissolved by the same catchment ID. The WS coverage is converted to the shapefile: WSC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">08260000</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> All King County WSC shapefile basins are fitted together using ArcGIS ArcToolBox command Integrate at 15 feet tolerance. Basins are merged together using the ArcToolBox Merge command into a GeoDataBase called DRNBASIN_NEW. Topology is created using "No Gaps" and "No Overlaps" rules. All topology errors are fixed in DRNBASIN_NEW. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> A copy of bigwater is edited to delete the rivers. An existing old copy of DRNBASIN was updated with the modified bigwater layer using the command UPDATE. The updated DRNBASIN is cleaned up to eliminate slivers between bigwater and dnrbasin. The conflated DRNBASIN to Bigwater is UPDATED with DRNBASIN_NEW, dissolved using the attribute catchment to produce the new drnbasin TOPO_CATCHMENT.
TOPO_CATCHMENT is cleaned of slivers, then the 3 child products (Basin, Watershed, and WRIA) are dissolved from topo_catchment. All four levels of topo_catchment are clipped with the King County boundary to produce TOPO_CATCHMENT_KC, TOPO_BASIN_KC, TOPO_WATERSHED_KC, and TOPO_WRIA_KC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Quality control was done by comparing the original DRNBASIN catchments IDs to the new Topo_Catchment catchment IDs. Any missing catchments were added by using the command UPDATE and then MERGING of the sliver polygons generated from the UPDATE around the polygon. Multi part polygons caused by the original MERGING and UPDATE corrections were EXPLODED then MERGED using DRNBASIN as a guide. </procdesc> <srcused Sync="TRUE">J:\basin\topo_catchment.xml</srcused> <procdate>20061017</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">07275200</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Split Upper White River basin into 4 basins: Lower White 100304, Greenwater 10036, Westfork 100305, Upper White stays 100303. Spit Skykomish basin into 6 basins: North Fork 70110, South Fork 70111, Beckler 70113, Miller 70112, Foss 70114, Tye 70115. Corrected Thorton & North Fork Tolt basin boundaries. </procdesc> <procdate>1-16-2008</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc Sync="TRUE">Dataset copied.</procdesc> <time Some catchments outside of King County have no ID value. Not all Basins have Sub-Basins.</logic> <complete>Topo_Catchment replaces DRNBASIN completely. The area that was updated is King County's Lidar extent. This includes all of King County and Basins in Snohomish that are part of the Lake Washington - Cedar Watershed.</complete> <lineage> <procstep> <procdesc> For each HYDROBASIN or TOPO_BASIN, a project area is built in Arc/Info 9.1 using the AML build_dem.aml. This AML builds a 2000 foot buffered Digital Elevation Model, Accumulation, and Slope grids for the basin area using the Bare Earth or Digital Ground Model Lidar grids. Clip existing WTRCRS per DRNBASIN's attribute BASIN_NAME or HYDROBASIN area. Import WTRCRS to a personal geodatabase. For WTRCRS, add field attributes DEPTH (Short, 4) for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses, RATE (Short, 4) for geometry accuracy rating, and NOTES (Text, 254) for additional information for each line. Create polygon Shapefiles "DEMFIX" and point "PRPT" for each basin. Add field attribute DEPTH (Short, 4) to shapefile "DEMFIX" for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses. Add attribute "CATCHMENT" (Text, 40) to "PRPT" for joining to existing DRNBASIN Polygon Attribute Table </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Create Arcmap project per basin and add basin data. Correct WTRCRS geometry using KC and USGS 2002 orthophotos, Lidar products elevation, slope, hillshade, and contours for referance in Arcmap. Place shapefile PRPT Pour Points per existing DRNBASIN catchments. Calc catchment ID to PRPT attribute "CATCHMENT". Add "DEMFIX" polygons as needed to facilitated water flow over obstacles i.e. roads crossing streams and calculate a depth. Export geodatabase WTRCRS to shapefile WTRCRS After the basin WTRCRS is corrected and Pour Points added for each catchment, the AML mk_ws.aml (Make Watershed) is used to produce the catchments for each basin. The mk_ws.aml converts shapefiles WTRCRS, DEMFIX, and PRPT to coverages. The lines of WTRCRS and polygons of DEMFIX are converted to grids. The grids "burn" or subtract cell values for a stream course into the DEM using the DEPTH value to facilitate the correct flow path though the DEM. Fills the DEM for sinkholes, Finds Flow Direction of the DEM, and the Flow Accumulation of cells. The cells with greater than 40,000 cells flowing into them are extracted to grid STRM40KG, then converted to coverage STRM40KG. PRPT coverage is converted to grid, then snaped using Grid command snappour to the STRM40KG grid. The Grid command WATERSHED deliniates the catchement watershed boundaries to grid WSG (Watershed Grid). Grid WSG is converted to coverage WS (Watershed). In ArcEdit, the existing label points in WS are replaced with the PRPT point labels that have the catchment attribute. The WS is polygon rebuilt, then blank attribute polygons are deleted, and duplicate catchments are dissolved by the same catchment ID. The WS coverage is converted to the shapefile: WSC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">08260000</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> All King County WSC shapefile basins are fitted together using ArcGIS ArcToolBox command Integrate at 15 feet tolerance. Basins are merged together using the ArcToolBox Merge command into a GeoDataBase called DRNBASIN_NEW. Topology is created using "No Gaps" and "No Overlaps" rules. All topology errors are fixed in DRNBASIN_NEW. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> A copy of bigwater is edited to delete the rivers. An existing old copy of DRNBASIN was updated with the modified bigwater layer using the command UPDATE. The updated DRNBASIN is cleaned up to eliminate slivers between bigwater and dnrbasin. The conflated DRNBASIN to Bigwater is UPDATED with DRNBASIN_NEW, dissolved using the attribute catchment to produce the new drnbasin TOPO_CATCHMENT.
TOPO_CATCHMENT is cleaned of slivers, then the 3 child products (Basin, Watershed, and WRIA) are dissolved from topo_catchment. All four levels of topo_catchment are clipped with the King County boundary to produce TOPO_CATCHMENT_KC, TOPO_BASIN_KC, TOPO_WATERSHED_KC, and TOPO_WRIA_KC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Quality control was done by comparing the original DRNBASIN catchments IDs to the new Topo_Catchment catchment IDs. Any missing catchments were added by using the command UPDATE and then MERGING of the sliver polygons generated from the UPDATE around the polygon. Multi part polygons caused by the original MERGING and UPDATE corrections were EXPLODED then MERGED using DRNBASIN as a guide. </procdesc> <srcused Sync="TRUE">J:\basin\topo_catchment.xml</srcused> <procdate>20061017</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">07275200</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Split Upper White River basin into 4 basins: Lower White 100304, Greenwater 10036, Westfork 100305, Upper White stays 100303. Spit Skykomish basin into 6 basins: North Fork 70110, South Fork 70111, Beckler 70113, Miller 70112, Foss 70114, Tye 70115. Corrected Thorton & North Fork Tolt basin boundaries. </procdesc> <procdate>1-16-2008</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc Sync="TRUE">Dataset copied.</procdesc> <time Sync="TRUE">08203900</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc>Each time TOPO_CATCHMENT is updated this feature class is updated by a dissolve and then clipped to the King County boundary.</procdesc> <metadata> <idinfo> <citation> <citeinfo> <origin>King County</origin> <pubdate>20061002</pubdate> <title>WRIA boundaries derived from terrain data - King County only</title> <edition>One</edition> <geoform Sync="TRUE">vector digital data</geoform> <pubinfo> <pubplace>King County, WA</pubplace> <publish>King County</publish> </pubinfo> <othercit>None</othercit> <onlink Sync="TRUE">\\gisimage\images\FTPData\DataStage\topo_wria_kc\topo_wria_kc</onlink></citeinfo> </citation> <descript> <abstract>DRNBASIN is replaced with a higher detail TOPO_CATCHMENT. The difference between the two is DRNBASIN was digitized from existing paper maps based on USGS quad maps in the early 1990s. While the TOPO_CATCHMENT was produced using Arc/Info GRID Watershed commands on 6 foot cell GRIDS built from LIDAR ascii ground model data. Topo_Catchment is higher in accuracy then DRNBASIN</abstract> <purpose>To replace existing King County Watershed layer DRNBASIN with higher accuracy watersheds based on Lidar. Watersheds delineate areas that water collect and flow out to another waterbody, i.e. a Basin, River, Lake or Sound</purpose> <supplinf>Topo_Catchment is the master layer and is dissolved to produce Topo_Basin, Topo_Watershed, and Topo_WRIA by attributes.</supplinf> </descript> <timeperd> <timeinfo> <rngdates> <begdate>20050601</begdate> <enddate>20061004</enddate> </rngdates> </timeinfo> <current>publication date</current> </timeperd> <status> <progress>Complete</progress> <update>As needed</update> </status> <spdom> <bounding> <westbc Sync="TRUE">-122.542057</westbc> <eastbc Sync="TRUE">-121.063186</eastbc> <northbc Sync="TRUE">47.788384</northbc> <southbc Sync="TRUE">47.073373</southbc> </bounding> </spdom> <keywords> <theme> <themekt>Not applicable</themekt> <themekey>hydro</themekey> <themekey>hydrology</themekey> <themekey>none</themekey> </theme> <place> <placekt>Not applicable</placekt> <placekey>King County, WA</placekey> <placekey>Pacific NW</placekey> <placekey>Washington state</placekey> </place> </keywords> <accconst>None</accconst> <useconst>King County data are made available with the understanding that they shall be used exclusively by the obtainer or his/her authorized agents. Some catchments outside of King County have no ID value. Not all Basins have Sub-Basins.</logic> <complete>Topo_Catchment replaces DRNBASIN completely. The area that was updated is King County's Lidar extent. This includes all of King County and Basins in Snohomish that are part of the Lake Washington - Cedar Watershed.</complete> <lineage> <procstep> <procdesc> For each HYDROBASIN or TOPO_BASIN, a project area is built in Arc/Info 9.1 using the AML build_dem.aml. This AML builds a 2000 foot buffered Digital Elevation Model, Accumulation, and Slope grids for the basin area using the Bare Earth or Digital Ground Model Lidar grids. Clip existing WTRCRS per DRNBASIN's attribute BASIN_NAME or HYDROBASIN area. Import WTRCRS to a personal geodatabase. For WTRCRS, add field attributes DEPTH (Short, 4) for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses, RATE (Short, 4) for geometry accuracy rating, and NOTES (Text, 254) for additional information for each line. Create polygon Shapefiles "DEMFIX" and point "PRPT" for each basin. Add field attribute DEPTH (Short, 4) to shapefile "DEMFIX" for DEM "Stream Burning" of water courses. Add attribute "CATCHMENT" (Text, 40) to "PRPT" for joining to existing DRNBASIN Polygon Attribute Table </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Create Arcmap project per basin and add basin data. Correct WTRCRS geometry using KC and USGS 2002 orthophotos, Lidar products elevation, slope, hillshade, and contours for referance in Arcmap. Place shapefile PRPT Pour Points per existing DRNBASIN catchments. Calc catchment ID to PRPT attribute "CATCHMENT". Add "DEMFIX" polygons as needed to facilitated water flow over obstacles i.e. roads crossing streams and calculate a depth. Export geodatabase WTRCRS to shapefile WTRCRS After the basin WTRCRS is corrected and Pour Points added for each catchment, the AML mk_ws.aml (Make Watershed) is used to produce the catchments for each basin. The mk_ws.aml converts shapefiles WTRCRS, DEMFIX, and PRPT to coverages. The lines of WTRCRS and polygons of DEMFIX are converted to grids. The grids "burn" or subtract cell values for a stream course into the DEM using the DEPTH value to facilitate the correct flow path though the DEM. Fills the DEM for sinkholes, Finds Flow Direction of the DEM, and the Flow Accumulation of cells. The cells with greater than 40,000 cells flowing into them are extracted to grid STRM40KG, then converted to coverage STRM40KG. PRPT coverage is converted to grid, then snaped using Grid command snappour to the STRM40KG grid. The Grid command WATERSHED deliniates the catchement watershed boundaries to grid WSG (Watershed Grid). Grid WSG is converted to coverage WS (Watershed). In ArcEdit, the existing label points in WS are replaced with the PRPT point labels that have the catchment attribute. The WS is polygon rebuilt, then blank attribute polygons are deleted, and duplicate catchments are dissolved by the same catchment ID. The WS coverage is converted to the shapefile: WSC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">08260000</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> All King County WSC shapefile basins are fitted together using ArcGIS ArcToolBox command Integrate at 15 feet tolerance. Basins are merged together using the ArcToolBox Merge command into a GeoDataBase called DRNBASIN_NEW. Topology is created using "No Gaps" and "No Overlaps" rules. All topology errors are fixed in DRNBASIN_NEW. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> A copy of bigwater is edited to delete the rivers. An existing old copy of DRNBASIN was updated with the modified bigwater layer using the command UPDATE. The updated DRNBASIN is cleaned up to eliminate slivers between bigwater and dnrbasin. The conflated DRNBASIN to Bigwater is UPDATED with DRNBASIN_NEW, dissolved using the attribute catchment to produce the new drnbasin TOPO_CATCHMENT.
TOPO_CATCHMENT is cleaned of slivers, then the 3 child products (Basin, Watershed, and WRIA) are dissolved from topo_catchment. All four levels of topo_catchment are clipped with the King County boundary to produce TOPO_CATCHMENT_KC, TOPO_BASIN_KC, TOPO_WATERSHED_KC, and TOPO_WRIA_KC. </procdesc> <procdate>20061004</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Quality control was done by comparing the original DRNBASIN catchments IDs to the new Topo_Catchment catchment IDs. Any missing catchments were added by using the command UPDATE and then MERGING of the sliver polygons generated from the UPDATE around the polygon. Multi part polygons caused by the original MERGING and UPDATE corrections were EXPLODED then MERGED using DRNBASIN as a guide. </procdesc> <srcused Sync="TRUE">J:\basin\topo_catchment.xml</srcused> <procdate>20061017</procdate> <time Sync="TRUE">07275200</time> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc> Split Upper White River basin into 4 basins: Lower White 100304, Greenwater 10036, Westfork 100305, Upper White stays 100303. Spit Skykomish basin into 6 basins: North Fork 70110, South Fork 70111, Beckler 70113, Miller 70112, Foss 70114, Tye 70115. Corrected Thorton & North Fork Tolt basin boundaries. </procdesc> <procdate>1-16-2008</procdate> </procstep> <procstep> <procdesc Sync="TRUE">Dataset copied.</procdesc> <time
